<TITLE> Blast set by militants kills Lebanese soldier </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAHR AL-BARED, Lebanon, July 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - An explosive booby-trap set by Islamist militants killed a Lebanese soldier on Tuesday at a Palestinian refugee camp convulsed by more than nine weeks of fighting. Security sources said a second soldier was missing in the rubble of a building brought down by the blast at Nahr al-Bared camp, where Fatah al-Islam militants are still resisting the army's slow advance towards their last strongholds. More than 81 militants and at least 41 civilians have also been killed in the battles that have devastated densely populated neighbourhoods that were once home to 40,000 refugees. Fatah al-Islam, a well-armed group of Palestinian, Lebanese and foreign Arabs wedded to al Qaeda's militant ideology, broke away from a Syrian-backed Palestinian faction last year. Nearly all Nahr al-Bared's residents have fled to other refugee camps in Lebanon. A UN official has said the cost of rebuilding will run into hundreds of millions of dollars. Palestinian sources say about 1,000 civilians remain in Nahr al-Bared, including the families of Fatah al-Islam fighters. The internal conflict, Lebanon's worst since the 1975-90 civil war, is sapping stability in a country already paralysed by a political crisis and shaken by fatal bombings, whose victims include two anti-Syrian politicians and six UN peacekeeping troops, in the past eight mont
